entry.title: Sync secure DNS template URI for automatic mode
entry.content:
CL:5317742 introduced network identifiers in the secure DNS template

URI. As a result, the template URIs are reevaluated every time the

default network changes. To prevent spamming shill with repeating

D-Bus calls, CL:5317742 introduced a check to enforce that shill is

only sent the template URIs if the values change after the

template reevaluation.



This check introduced an error. The template URIs have initial

user-set values which are overridden by policy. If the policy is not

set, the template URIs have the same initial user-set values before and

after the template reevaluation. The check introduced in CL:5317742

prevents the initial user-set template URIs to be sent to shill.



This CL ensures that the initial user-set values of the template URIs

are forwarded to shill.



Bug: b/331126256

Test: tast run $DUT network.DNSProxy.chrome_doh_automatic

entry.title: cros: cache process's priority sent to resourced
entry.content:
DBusSchedqosStateHandler caches the latest process priority in its

internal map because base::Process::GetPriority() is a synchronous API.



To prevent leak of cache, processes need to call

`base::Process::InitializePriority()` and

`base::Process::ForgetPriority()` explicitly. The browser process itself

entry.title: [FspCache] Enable basic read/write support for ContentCache
entry.content:
The `ContentCache` is acting like a hub to facilitate reading, writing

and guarding access to files that are stored on the disk. This adds

very basic support for read/write via the FSP API.



Writers are supported iff they are writing contiguous chunks that

haven't been written before. This precludes random access writers and

concurrent writers to the same file. Readers are allowed random access

iff the bytes requested are within the range that is available on disk.



If any ContentCache streaming operation fails to write the requested

bytes to disk yet the underlying FSP operation succeeded it will

always appear as a success to the caller. Currently, however, if a

local reader fails this will return a failure to the caller.



Bug: b/331280525, b/331280403

entry.title: [Extensions] Clean up unacked events on render process shutdown.
entry.content:
Before this change, we would never remove any unacked events in

`EventAckData` when a render process goes away. This means that events

that were unacked when the render process went away would stay in

`unacked_events_` for the remainder of the browser session (a memory

leak).



After this change, when the render process goes away we observer this

and remove any `unacked_events_` for that render process' id.

entry.title: Mahi: Update panel scroll view to use box layout to avoid layout issue
entry.content:
We are currently using a FillLayout for the scroll contents view.

However, we run into a problem with FillLayout in which:



- View A use a FillLayout, and has a parent of view B and C.

- When B shows and C hides, A has the same size as B.

- After clicking a button, B will hide and C will show, A still has the

same size as B (whereas it should have the size of C now).



We do not have this problem when we use a BoxLayout, so this CL switch

the scroll contents view to use a BoxLayout instead.



Fixed: b:330395908

entry.title: [DNR] Matched allow rules now affect future rule matching stages
entry.content:
If an allow rule is matched in an earlier request stage, the rule will

take effect in later request stages when rule matching occurs by

imposing a minimum priority.



E.g.

If a request matches with an allow rule of priority 3 in onBeforeRequest

and a block rule of priority 4 in onHeadersReceived, the request will

be blocked



If a request matches with an allow rule of priority 3 in onBeforeRequest

and a block rule of priority 1 in onHeadersReceived, the request will

NOT be blocked since the allow rule's priority exceeds that of the

blocked rule.



Similar to how allow rules work before, they will also prevent lower

priority rules from being marked as matched.

entry.title: media: Introduce MojoStableVideoDecoder
entry.content:
This CL introduces a new class, MojoStableVideoDecoder, which is

analogous to the existing MojoVideoDecoder but communicates over a

stable::mojom::StableVideoDecoder connection instead of a

mojom::VideoDecoder. This is intended to be used with the GTFO OOP-VD

path (go/oopvd-gtfo-dd).



The general approach will be to delegate most functionality to an

OOPVideoDecoder which already knows how to talk to a

stable::mojom::StableVideoDecoder and is currently used for the regular

OOP-VD path.



This CL mainly introduces the skeleton and unit testing infrastructure.

It doesn't do much in terms of actual functionality except for one

thing: the OOPVideoDecoder assumes that the supported configurations are

known prior to calling Initialize() on it. When the OOPVideoDecoder runs

in the GPU process (for regular OOP-VD), this is guaranteed by the

InterfaceFactoryImpl. For GTFO, the OOPVideoDecoder will run in the

renderer process and it's up to the MojoStableVideoDecoder to guarantee

the above requirement. Another requirement is that the OOPVideoDecoder

expects to be constructed, used, and destroyed on the same sequence.

A media::VideoDecoder should be able to be constructed on one sequence

and thereafter be used and destroyed on another. The

MojoStableVideoDecoder strives to be fully compliant with the

media::VideoDecoder API so that it can be a drop-in replacement for the

MojoVideoDecoder.



Hence, the solution will be to lazily create the OOPVideoDecoder and

initialize it only when the supported configurations are known. Part of

this logic is implemented in this CL and the rest of the initialization

is done in a follow-up CL.



Note: at first glance, one might be tempted to templatize the existing

MojoVideoDecoder so that it can be used with either a

stable::mojom::StableVideoDecoder or a mojom::VideoDecoder connection.

This *might* work now because the two Mojo interfaces are currently

similar. However, in the long term, the two interfaces will probably

diverge due to the versioning constraints of

stable::mojom::StableVideoDecoder and the MojoVideoDecoder would have to

increase in complexity to handle those two paths. Additionally, the

threat model addressed by MojoVideoDecoder is fundamentally different

than the one addressed by the MojoStableVideoDecoder: in the former

case, we can assume a trust gradient between the renderer (client) and

the GPU process (service) whereas in the latter, we haven't established

a trust gradient between the renderer (client) and the video decoder

utility process (service). Therefore, the MojoStableVideoDecoder will

need to do more validation.



Thus, overall, it seems better to just have a separate class that deals

with these concerns.
